			<DIV>It is nerfs (not bug fix, NERF!) that are driving players away from EQ. Necros were not terribly happy with the original version of SoD. To drasticly cut the DPS, without mentioning it in a patch message is a huge insult to everyone in the Necro community. This comes after the famous statment that "our nefing days are behind us". Other AA nerfs in the past were only done in extreme situations, such as the Manaburn nerf which was done after teams of wizards went around blowing away Kunark dragons. It seems that now days, developers feel that they can release untested, unparsed code and then just nerf it without telling anyone. Players parse their DPS, determine where to spend their AAs and come to depend on their abilities. A nerf like this takes away something that the players have put in the time to earn.</FONT></DIV>
<DIV></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Just answer me this: Why was so much thaught and consideration put into the Manaburn nerf yet the SoD nerf can be implemented by a single developer without even mentioning it in the patch message? What was it about the original SoD that made it so unbalancing to the game? How can we the players possibly know what features of an AA are intended vs which are unintentional bugs and why should we even have to worry about that?</FONT></DIV>	
