			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=Necromancers&message.id=1289#M1289">59</a> of 121
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 1087 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Kytherea wrote:<BR>
<DIV>When we found out about the change to SoD Brenlo and I went to those in chanrge of making changes as well as those in charge or those people who make changes.&nbsp; It was then that it was decided that aa points would be refunded.&nbsp; I am sorry but the changes to SoD are not up for discussion at this time to be reverted back to what the ability was prior to the change.&nbsp; Development will refund the points as soon as they can.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Ky</DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV>
<P>Ky, while I wouldn't go so far as the above poster in saying <EM>nobody</EM> will re-purchase this AA, I will agree and say that there will be quite a sharp decrease in the number of people who choose to use it, as it's utility has been quite substantially reduced. Here is the issue that I see here:</P>
<UL>
<LI>SoD goes through quite a number of balance changes based on player feedback in beta for Gates</LI>
<LI>Players notice that it does a substantial ammount of damage if the pets are summoned in melee range and /feedback this info to the devs asking if it is intentional, and they don't get a response.</LI>
<LI>SoD goes live and stays that way a couple months - Players develop substantial interest in the ability</LI>
<LI>A developer notices that the archer pets are doing substantial melee damage - no information on how he got this info</LI>
<LI>Developer changes the AA ability and neglects to inform the playerbase</LI>
<LI>Playerbase notices change, gets in an uproar, points will be refunded.</LI></UL>
<P>Ok, I don't think there is much to dispute about the facts as laid out above. Here's where I really don't understand things though. It seems to me that despite the feedback that the devs received during beta for Gates of Discord (asking if this is as intended) it went live. That means to me that either&nbsp;</P>
<OL>
<LI>the devs at the time were fine with the way it was</LI>
<LI>the devs did not see / read the feedback that was sent, or </LI>
<LI>the devs did see it, and failed to adjust the ability prior to end of beta, and resubmit the ability for player feedback again.</LI></OL>
<P>Case 2 and 3 bring up an intriguing possibility, that the dev that adjusted the ability either is just now going over the tuning from beta - either going from their own notes, or just now getting to the feedback that was sent during beta. Case 1 brings up an issue of the right hand not knowing what the left is doing. It also brings to question how the testing of that particular ability was done from the dev's perspective. Was it....</P>
<OL>
<LI>a_dev_001 puts in some theoretical numbers for the ranged attack, forgets to turn off melee damage and lets playerbase test to see if ability is broken</LI>
<LI>a_dev_001 designs AA ability, and parses for themselves how much damage it does... both melee and ranged?</LI>
<LI>a_dev_001 designs AA ability, and only parses for themselves how much damage it does in ranged combat?</LI></OL>
<P>It's a case of what is "as intended"?? - I can deal with the melee damage not being as intended. They wanted it to be a ranged ability, which is cool with me. I can deal with the fact that the points will be refunded. Thats fine. I can deal with the fact that the changes were made without telling us, and we're now being informed. While irksome, mistakes happen, and people are human.&nbsp; That to me is actually a small error.&nbsp; What I don't understand, and find quite disconcerting, is how a <EM>large error</EM> such as ignoring player feedback, or getting to it 2 months after release when the information was supplied when it was <EM>supposed to be</EM> -- that is, in beta.</P>
<P>The playerbase thought that this ability was ok to go live, and thought that it was pretty nifty in beta, and asked "hey, this swarm pet is pretty neat, it does damage based on your situation, can do more damage in melee, less at ranged, makes the payer think, yadda yadda. Seems cool to me - is the melee really intended? If it's not, we'd probably like to up the ranged damage some, thanks very much" - signed the players.&nbsp; </P>
<P>So -- was the overall damage as intended and the devs just didn't move the additional dps generated from melee to range? Or, did they intend for this ability to do the current damage it does at ranged, and no melee as the current change has it?</P>
<P>Also Ky, I note that you said that it is not open for discussion to be reverted back to the way it was. I also most certainly note what you did NOT say, which is whether or not they are open for it to be changed in other ways (such as modifying cost, modifying the damage the pets do with their ranged attack, etc).&nbsp; </P>
<P>Thanks for the time and effort you've put in so far Ky. You've done a good job in relaying information back and forth in a digestible form to the dev team from and to us. What we'd like back from the devs (I think I can speak for quite a few players) is a bit more of the why's, and an actual dialogue. I know there are a number of players that try to understand why changes are made / not made from a balance perspective, and I think&nbsp;both the devs and the players would&nbsp;get more out of an open conversation, than the current "gather raw information from the players" and then hand down decisions by fiat, with a "because this is the way it's going to be, now quit whining." model that it *seems* to be. The effort you folks (Brenlo, Ashlanne, and yourself Ky) are putting forward <EM>is</EM> a step in the right direction, and it could be so much more.&nbsp; </P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
