			<P>The real problem here is that an employee of SoE,&nbsp;the dev that Ky talked to, admitted making a mistake yet we, the customers, are going to suffer for it. The dev that implmented this AA&nbsp;could&nbsp;never have&nbsp;tested it. If he had, he would have found out that the pets mele because it is impossible to miss.&nbsp;So if he had never tested it, how did he know what the proper amount of DPS was supposed to be? My guess is that this feature was implemented with very little thaught to blanance since how do you balance something you never even test? This admission of a mistake and nerf demonstrate yet again that there needs to be better management oversight of the EQ developer team.</P>
<P>For the record, I write software for a living. If I released a program with some mistake that helped the users in some way, I would never dream of punishing them by taking it away. I also spend a lot of time testing my software after I write it to make sure it works the way that I intend. If I find I have released software with bugs, I will fix it as soon as possible and certainly before implementing any additional features.</P>
<P>The attitude that SoE is taking here is demonstrating a clear lack of respect for its customers and a great deal of arrogance on the part of the developer.</P>
