		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV>
<DIV>I understand this was a "fix" for something that wasn't "working as intended". But come on, was it really so incredibly overpowering that&nbsp;it's worth the animosity that's generated&nbsp;by "fixing"&nbsp;it? If it would have been originally implemented as the devs claim&nbsp;it was intended, it wouldn't be much of an issue, since most wouldn't have bothered to buy it in the first place. However, it's the constant giving and then later taking away that really irritates people.&nbsp; Besides, it sounds like there was plenty of feedback given in the Beta to get it to the state at which it was released.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Christ guys, if you're going to err on the side of caution, release skills, spells, etc that are <U>underpowered</U> and "fix" them later to make&nbsp;them worth getting. Instead, you do the <STRONG>exact</STRONG> opposite by releasing things you apparently haven't fully thought about, and then nerf them later. Bait and switch, anyone?</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Call it a fix if you want, but it comes across as a nerf since you're taking something away. All you're doing is ticking people off, keep it up, and there won't be many people left to tick off after a while.</DIV>	
		</td></tr>
